<subSubSection id="C3246572FF9FC930FF62FC95FD63FC9E" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B8136F9FF9FC930FF62FC95FD63FC9E" blockId="62.[151,1437,690,1437]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis id="B94AEAEBFF9FC930FF62FC95FEC0FCFA" bold="true" box="[199,334,799,825]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name refers to the Tambor community, original inhabitants of the area that now encompasses the Jaú National Park; noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3246572FF9FC930FF62FCECFC5FFBD2" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B8136F9FF9FC930FF62FCECFC5FFBD2" blockId="62.[151,1437,690,1437]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis id="B94AEAEBFF9FC930FF62FCECFECCFC43" bold="true" box="[199,322,870,896]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E4D7AFF9FC930FE11FCEDFDA5FC42" authority="Rheims &amp; Jäger, 2022" authorityName="Rheims &amp; Jäger" authorityYear="2022" box="[436,555,871,897]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Meri" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tambor" status="spec. nov.">
<emphasis id="B94AEAEBFF9FC930FE11FCEDFDA5FC42" box="[436,555,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">M. tambor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B94AEAEBFF9FC930FD96FCEDFD28FC42" bold="true" box="[563,678,871,897]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2795790FF9FC930FD96FCEDFD28FC42" box="[563,678,871,897]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" rank="species">spec. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
resemble those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E4D7AFF9FC930FCD9FCEDFC66FC43" authority="Rheims &amp; Jäger, 2022" authorityName="Rheims &amp; Jäger" authorityYear="2022" box="[892,1000,871,896]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Meri" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vanini" status="spec. nov.">
<emphasis id="B94AEAEBFF9FC930FCD9FCEDFC66FC43" box="[892,1000,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">M. vanini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B94AEAEBFF9FC930FC55FCEDFBEDFC42" bold="true" box="[1008,1123,871,897]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2795790FF9FC930FC55FCEDFBEDFC42" box="[1008,1123,871,897]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" rank="species">spec. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13052A7CFF9FC930FBD7FCEDFA81FC42" box="[1138,1295,870,897]" captionStart="FIGURES 285–291" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1792,1816]" captionTargetBox="[165,1415,317,1757]" captionTargetId="figure-93@70.[155,1432,309,1769]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 285–291. Meri vanini spec. nov. 285–288 male (MPEG 30859, paratype), left palp (285 prolateral, 286 ventral, 287 retrolateral, 288 detail of embolus, ventral); 289–291 female (MZSP 37241, paratype) (289 epigyne, 290 vulva, 291 schematic course of internal duct system). C—conductor; E—embolus; EP—epigynal pocket; FD—fertilization duct; ft—first turn of duct system; GP—glandular projection; LL—lateral lobe; MS—median septum; PTA—prolateral tibial apophysis; RpP—retro proximal projection; RTA—retrolateral tibial projection; SdP—subdistal projection; SP—spermathecae; ST—subtegulum; tp—tegular protrusion. Scale lines: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6550516" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6550516/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Figs 285–288</figureCitation>
) by the palp with RTA distally blunt and embolus bulging prolaterally at base, with long, distad, laminar subdistal projection and barely conspicuous membranous area (see 
<figureCitation id="13052A7CFF9FC930FD03FC25FC89FC0A" box="[678,775,943,969]" captionStart="FIGURES 99–102" captionStartId="30.[151,264,1875,1899]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,669,1852]" captionTargetId="figure-289@30.[151,1436,669,1852]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURES 99–102. 99 Meri vanini spec. nov. 99, 101 IBSP 227036, male; 102 IBSP 5352, female; 100 Meri conduri spec. nov. MPEG 30809, male. 99 epiandrium, epiandrous spigots (arrows point to clusters of spigots); 100 right palp, embolus, detail of membranous region; 101 right palp, embolus, detail of membranous region; 102 left palp, sensory setae. mr—membranous region." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6550269" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6550269/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Fig. 100</figureCitation>
). They are distinguished from the latter species by the RTA longer than wide (
<figureCitation id="13052A7CFF9FC930FEC5FC59FE30FC2E" box="[352,446,978,1005]" captionStart="FIGURES 253–259" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1813,1837]" captionTargetBox="[163,1422,393,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-80@63.[154,1434,381,1790]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 253–259. 253–256 Meri tambor spec. nov., male (INPA 3522), left palp (253 prolateral, 254 ventral, 255 retrolateral, 256 detail of embolus); 257–259 Meri tapirapeco spec. nov., female (INPA) (257 epigyne, 258 vulva, 259 schematic course of internal duct system). C—conductor; E—embolus; EP— epigynal pocket; FD—fertilization duct; ft—first turn of duct system; GP—glandular projection; LL—lateral lobe; MS—median septum; PTA—prolateral tibial apophysis; RpP—retro proximal projection; RTA—retrolateral tibial projection; SdP—subdistal projection; SP—spermathecae; tp—tegular protrusion. Scale lines: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6550500" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6550500/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Fig. 255</figureCitation>
) and embolus bulging retrolaterally at base (
